What the question is really asking is: can man have free will and an omnipotent god at the same time? <br>
Let us first look at the powers which an omnipotent god would possess, he would: <br>
· Have the ability to control everything down to the subatomic level; <br>
· Above all else he would have an absolute knowledge of the past, present and future. <br>
As a consequence of god having created the universe he would have a flawless knowledge of the laws that govern our universe, the rules to which everything must adhere. As such all matter in the universe must exactly follow the guidelines which god has set from the beginning of the universe until the end of time. <br>
In other words god knew everything when he created the universe and the rules which everything must adhere to. Taking this into account we can deduce the following two statements: <br>
· At any time in the universe god will know exactly what will happen at any other time in the universe; <br>
· The condition of the present, down to the exact detail became inevitable at the point when the universe was created. <br>
(This last one is a little tricky to grasp. In other words, the manner in which the universe was created defined exactly what will happen in that universe at any given point in time.) <br>
The conclusions that can be drawn from the preceding two statements imply something no one wants to accept. This odd pantomime that we call life is all just following a cruel, inescapable script ordained by the most vindictive of gods. <br>
If god is omnipotent the past, present and future was defined with the creation of the universe. This makes free will impossible because man is following an unavoidable track, making his way to a certain end. <br>
With this in mind, let us return to the focus of the question. Can man have free will and an omnipotent god at the same time? The answer has become clear to me. Infinite knowledge and power makes the notion of free will impossible. <br>
So now, only if god does not exist you are presented with a choice, would you rather have free will, or an omnipotent god? <br>
<br>
I did not specify a religion on purpose, this should apply to all gods of infinite power. <br>
<br>
Personally I dont have to make the choice. In actual fact I think that the universe was never created, and that the term god is in dire need of a re-definition. Still my argument makes interesting reading if you believe that the universe was created by a god in the conventional sense. <br>
